Trim the @pak choi{1%unit}(trimmed and thinly sliced widthways).

Trim the @carrot{2%unit}(trimmed and sliced into ½ cm rounds, no need to peel).

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%unit}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Zest half the @lime{1/2%unit}(zested) (double for 4p) then cut in half.

Place a #pan{} over medium-high heat (no oil).

When the pan is hot, add the @Irish beef mince{250%grams} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Lower the heat and add the carrots with a drizzle of @?oil{to taste} if necessary. Cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

Add the garlic, @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} and @chicken stock{1%sachet}.

Add @water{100%ml} (double for 4p) and the pak choi, then mix everything together. Simmer, stirring frequently until the liquid has reduced by half, ~{4-5%minutes}.

When the beef is ready stir through the @hoisin sauce{2%sachet}, @sugar{2%tsp} (double for 4p), and a squeeze of lime juice to taste. Add a splash of @?water{to taste} if necessary.

Gently separate the @udon noodles{300%grams} with your hands then add them to the pan.

Toss the lime zest and noodles gently in the sauce until noodles are softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove from the heat, taste and season to taste with salt, pepper and sugar.

Share the fragrant beef noodles between your #bowls{}.

Chop any remaining lime into wedges and serve alongside.